(40, 13, 38, 44, 13, 10, 10, 'children of the wicked one', 'Children of the Kingdom vs. Devil', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the ''children of the kingdom'' and the ''child of the devil.'' Both passages emphasize the distinction between those aligned with righteousness and those who oppose it.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 38, 50, 3, 18, 19, 'children of the wicked one', 'Connection of Good and Wicked', 'This connection highlights the distinction between the ''children of the kingdom'' and the ''enemies of the cross of Christ.'' Both passages emphasize the contrast between those aligned with God and those who pursue earthly desires.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 38, 62, 3, 8, 10, 'children of the kingdom', 'Children of God vs. Devil', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between the children of God and the children of the devil. Matthew identifies the good seed as the children of the kingdom, while 1 John contrasts those who commit sin as being of the devil.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 38, 1, 3, 15, 15, 'the children of the wicked one', 'Connection of Seeds and Enmity', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''seed'' representing different lineages. Matthew speaks of ''children of the kingdom'' and ''children of the wicked one,'' while Genesis introduces enmity between ''thy seed and her seed.'' This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between good and evil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 38, 60, 1, 23, 23, 'the good seed are the children', 'Connection of Seed Imagery', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''seed'' in both passages. Matthew refers to ''good seed'' as children of the kingdom, while 1 Peter contrasts ''corruptible seed'' with ''incorruptible'' seed, emphasizing the nature of believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 38, 40, 13, 19, 19, 'the wicked one', 'Connection of the Wicked One', 'Both passages emphasize the role of ''the wicked one'' in relation to the word of the kingdom. In Matthew 13:38, the wicked one is contrasted with the children of the kingdom, while in Matthew 13:19, he actively takes away the seed sown in the heart.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 40, 13, 49, 49, 'the end of the world', 'End of the World Connection', 'Both passages emphasize ''the end of the world'' and describe the role of angels in separating the wicked from the just. This connection highlights the final judgment and the divine authority of angels in the harvest.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 66, 14, 15, 19, 'the harvest is the end of the world', 'Harvest and Reaping Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of harvest, with Matthew 13:39 mentioning the harvest as ''the end of the world'' and Revelation 14:15-19 depicting the reaping of the earth. This connection highlights the role of angels as reapers in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 40, 25, 31, 31, 'the harvest is the end of the world', 'Connection of End Times and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the end of the world and the role of angels in the final judgment. Matthew 13:39 refers to angels as reapers at the harvest, while Matthew 25:31 describes the Son of Man coming with angels to judge.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 29, 3, 13, 13, 'the harvest is the end of the world', 'Harvest and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of harvest as a time of judgment. Matthew refers to the harvest as the end of the world, while Joel describes the harvest as ripe due to wickedness. This connection highlights the theme of divine retribution.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 66, 19, 20, 20, 'the harvest is the end of the world', 'End Times and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the end of the world and divine judgment. Matthew speaks of the harvest at the end, while Revelation describes the judgment of the beast and false prophet.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 53, 1, 7, 10, 'the reapers are the angels', 'Connection of Judgment and Angels', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in the final judgment. Matthew describes angels as reapers at the end of the world, while 2 Thessalonians mentions mighty angels executing vengeance upon the disobedient.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 39, 49, 6, 11, 12, 'the enemy that sowed them is the devil', 'Spiritual Warfare Against the Devil', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the devil as an adversary. Matthew identifies the devil as the enemy sowing tares, while Ephesians instructs believers to stand against the wiles of the devil, highlighting the spiritual battle faced by Christians.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 40, 40, 13, 39, 39, NULL, 'Connection of Harvest and End', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the harvest as the end of the world, linking the gathering of tares to the final judgment. The mention of the enemy and the reapers in the second passage further connects the roles of the devil and angels in this eschatological event.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 40, 24, 31, 31, 'gather out of his kingdom', 'Gathering of the Elect', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in gathering individuals. In Matthew 13:41, the angels gather those who offend, while in Matthew 24:31, they gather the elect from all directions.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 40, 18, 7, 7, 'all things that offend', 'Connection of Offences in Matthew', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''offences'' and their consequences. Matthew 13:41 speaks of gathering out those who offend, while Matthew 18:7 warns of the woe that comes from offences. This connection highlights the seriousness of causing offences within the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 61, 2, 1, 2, 'all things that offend', 'Judgment of False Teachers', 'Both passages emphasize the removal of those who offend and do iniquity. Matthew speaks of gathering out those who offend, while 2 Peter warns against false teachers who bring in heresies, leading many astray.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 66, 21, 27, 27, 'all things that offend', 'Judgment and Exclusion Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of exclusion from God''s kingdom due to iniquity and defilement. Both passages emphasize the removal of those who offend or work abomination, ensuring only the righteous enter.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 45, 2, 8, 9, 'them which do iniquity', 'Judgment and Consequences of Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against those who do iniquity. Both passages emphasize the consequences of unrighteousness and the gathering of those who offend from the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 45, 2, 16, 16, 'the Son of man shall send forth his angels', 'Judgment and Gathering of Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment present in both passages. Matthew emphasizes the gathering of those who offend, while Romans speaks of God judging the secrets of men, both pointing to a future reckoning by Jesus Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 41, 58, 1, 6, 7, NULL, 'Angels and Their Roles', 'This connection highlights the role of angels in both passages. In Matthew, angels gather those who offend, while in Hebrews, angels are described as ministers and spirits, indicating their active role in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 40, 13, 50, 50, 'there shall be wailing and gnashing of teeth', 'Connection of Judgment Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting into a furnace of fire, highlighting a theme of judgment and punishment. The repetition of ''wailing and gnashing of teeth'' reinforces the severity of this fate.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 40, 8, 12, 12, 'there shall be wailing and gnashing of teeth', 'Weeping and Gnashing of Teeth', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences for those excluded from the kingdom, highlighting a similar theme of punishment. The phrases ''gnashing of teeth'' and ''weeping'' in both verses illustrate the anguish experienced by those cast out.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 42, 16, 23, 24, 'furnace of fire', 'Connection of Torment and Fire', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of torment in fire. Matthew describes a furnace of fire with wailing, while Luke depicts a man in hell experiencing torment in flames.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 66, 20, 10, 10, 'furnace of fire', 'Connection of Eternal Torment', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of torment in a fiery setting. Matthew describes a furnace of fire, while Revelation speaks of a lake of fire where torment occurs.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 27, 3, 6, 6, 'furnace of fire', 'Connection of Fiery Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize a fiery furnace as a place of punishment. Matthew speaks of a furnace of fire for the wicked, while Daniel describes a fiery furnace for those who refuse to worship. This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment through fire.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 66, 19, 20, 20, 'there shall be wailing and gnashing of teeth', 'Connection of Judgment Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine judgment and punishment. Matthew 13:42 speaks of a furnace of fire, while Revelation 19:20 describes a lake of fire, illustrating the fate of the wicked.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 42, 19, 21, 9, 9, 'furnace of fire', 'Fire and Divine Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine wrath and punishment through fire. The imagery of a ''furnace of fire'' in Matthew parallels the ''fiery oven'' in Psalms, highlighting the destructive nature of God''s anger.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 43, 27, 12, 3, 3, 'shine forth as the sun', 'Righteousness and Shining', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the righteous shining forth. Matthew speaks of the righteous shining as the sun, while Daniel describes the wise shining as brightness and stars. This connection highlights the reward for those who lead others to righteousness.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 43, 40, 11, 15, 15, NULL, 'Call to Listen', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''he that hath ears to hear, let him hear,'' highlighting the importance of attentive listening to divine messages. This connection underscores a recurring theme in Jesus'' teachings about receptiveness to spiritual truths.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
